 BANYO TEMITAYO THE Nigeria Civil Aviation Authority, on Tuesday, announced the suspension of Azman Air’s flight operations, citing series of safety incidents involving the airline’s Boeing 737 aircraft. This was disclosed in a statement signed by the Director General, NCAA, Capt. Musa Nuhu. He said the airline’s operations had been suspended with immediate effect, pursuant to Section 35 (2) of the Civil Aviation Act, 2006 and Part 1.3.3.3 (A) of the Nigeria Civil Aviation Regulations (Nig.CARs) 2015. The statement read, ”Following series of incidents involving Azman Air Boeing 737 aircraft, the Nigerian Civil Aviation Authority (NCAA) has, pursuant to Section 35 (2) of the Civil Aviation Act, 2006 and Part 1.3.3.3 (A) of the Nigeria Civil Aviation Regulations (Nig.CARs) 2015, suspended the operations of all the Boeing 737 Aircraft in the Fleet of Azman Air Services Limited, with effect from March 15, 2021. “The suspension is to enable the Authority conduct an audit of the airline to determine the root cause(s) of the incidents, and recommend corrective actions to forestall re-occurrence. “The NCAA regrets the inconvenience this action may cause to the public, particularly to Azman Air passengers but the need to ensure the safety of Air Transport and protect the public interest cannot be compromised.” “The Nigerian Civil Aviation Authority will continue to ensure compliance to its regulations in the interest of safety and will view any violation(s) seriously,” the Agency said. Azman Air had earlier released a statement, saying that it was undergoing an audit of its safety processes. It said, ”Due to our strong stance on safety, Azman Air will be undergoing an audit of its safety processes as supervised by the regulators. “In this regard, all our operations are hereby suspended. We are on our toes to restore operations within a short period. Kindly accept our apologies.” 